# Single env template for both web and worker production hosts.
#
# THIS FILE IS THE SOURCE OF TRUTH for which env vars web.service and
# worker.service expect. Placeholders below get substituted at deploy time
# (`envsubst`) with values pulled from GitHub:
#
#   - GitHub Repository â†’ Settings â†’ Secrets    â†’ for sensitive values
#   - GitHub Repository â†’ Settings â†’ Variables  â†’ for non-sensitive config
#
# The matching list lives in `.github/workflows/pipeline.yml` (deploy-web
# and deploy-worker render steps share one env block â€” anything you add
# here must be added there too, and set in GitHub UI).
#
# Why a single shared template (and identical env files on web + worker):
# both processes use the same Postgres, the same S3, the same Vertex AI.
# Variables that only one side actually reads (e.g. NEXTAUTH_URL on web,
# OUTBOX_BATCH_SIZE on worker) are simply ignored on the other side. This
# avoids the classification headache and keeps both env files in lockstep.
#
# To rotate any value: change it in GitHub UI â†’ re-run the deploy.

###############################################################################
# Runtime mode
###############################################################################
NODE_ENV=${NODE_ENV}
HOSTNAME=${HOSTNAME}
PORT=${PORT}

###############################################################################
# Database â€” managed Timeweb DBaaS (DATABASE_URL is a SECRET â€” embeds password)
###############################################################################
DATABASE_URL=${DATABASE_URL}

###############################################################################
# NextAuth + Yandex ID OAuth (web reads; worker ignores)
###############################################################################
NEXTAUTH_URL=${NEXTAUTH_URL}
AUTH_SECRET=${AUTH_SECRET}
YANDEX_CLIENT_ID=${YANDEX_CLIENT_ID}
YANDEX_CLIENT_SECRET=${YANDEX_CLIENT_SECRET}

